FIRST — WHAT IS NLB
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NLB = Network Load Balancer
ALB = Application Load Balancer

NLB works at Layer 4 (TCP/UDP)
ALB works at Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS)


CAN NLB DO WEIGHTED TARGET GROUPS?
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

ALB → weighted TG   ✅ YES supported
NLB → weighted TG   ❌ NO not supported


WHY NLB CANNOT DO WEIGHTS
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NLB works at TCP level
it does not understand HTTP
it has no concept of:
  → weighted routing
  → path based routing
  → header based routing
  → host based routing

NLB just forwards TCP packets
no intelligence ❌


COMPARISON
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Feature               ALB             NLB
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Layer                 7 (HTTP)        4 (TCP/UDP)
weighted TG           ✅ yes          ❌ no
Blue/Green            ✅ yes          ❌ no
Canary                ✅ yes          ❌ no
path routing          ✅ yes          ❌ no
host routing          ✅ yes          ❌ no
header routing        ✅ yes          ❌ no
performance           good            ultra high ✅
latency               milliseconds    microseconds ✅
static IP             ❌ no          ✅ yes
SSL termination       ✅ yes          ✅ yes
websockets            ✅ yes          ✅ yes
TCP/UDP apps          ❌ no          ✅ yes
HTTP apps             ✅ yes          ❌ not ideal
price                 higher          lower


WHEN TO USE NLB
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NLB is used for:
  → gaming servers (UDP)
  → IoT applications
  → real time streaming
  → apps needing static IP
  → extreme low latency
  → non HTTP traffic
  → TCP based apps

NLB is NOT used for:
  → Blue/Green ❌
  → Canary ❌
  → weighted routing ❌
  → HTTP routing rules ❌


SO FOR BLUE/GREEN AND CANARY
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

always use ALB ✅
never NLB ❌


WORKAROUND WITH NLB (complex)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

if you MUST use NLB and need Blue/Green:

  use Route53 weighted routing
  instead of NLB weights

  Route53
    → record A weight 100 → NLB-Blue → EC2 old
    → record B weight 0   → NLB-Green → EC2 new

  switch at DNS level
  not at load balancer level
  but DNS has TTL delay ⚠️
  not instant like ALB ⚠️


INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

"NLB does not support weighted target groups
 because it operates at Layer 4 TCP level
 and has no HTTP routing intelligence.
 Blue/Green and Canary require weighted
 target groups so we must use ALB.
 If NLB is required for performance reasons
 we can achieve Blue/Green at DNS level
 using Route53 weighted routing but it
 has TTL delay unlike instant ALB switching." ✅

-------------------------------------------------

Target Group NLB vs ALB

----------------------------

YES NLB HAS TARGET GROUPS
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NLB → TG → EC2s   ✅ yes it has TG

but NLB TG is different from ALB TG


WHAT NLB TG CAN DO
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NLB TG supports:
  → register EC2 instances    ✅
  → register IP addresses     ✅
  → register Lambda           ❌ no (ALB only)
  → health checks             ✅
  → TCP traffic forward       ✅


WHAT NLB TG CANNOT DO
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NLB TG does NOT support:
  → weighted routing          ❌
  → multiple TG with weights  ❌
  → forward to 2 TGs          ❌
  → path based rules          ❌
  → host based rules          ❌


THE KEY DIFFERENCE
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

ALB LISTENER RULE:
  forward action → multiple TGs with weight ✅

  TG-Blue  weight = 80
  TG-Green weight = 20

NLB LISTENER RULE:
  forward action → only ONE TG ❌

  TG → EC2s
  no weight
  no multiple TGs
  just forward everything


VISUAL DIFFERENCE
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

ALB:
  Internet
    ↓
  ALB
    ↓
  Listener (port 80)
    ↓
  Rule → forward
    ├── TG-Blue  (weight 80)  ✅
    └── TG-Green (weight 20)  ✅

NLB:
  Internet
    ↓
  NLB
    ↓
  Listener (port 80)
    ↓
  forward → ONE TG only ❌
              ↓
            EC2s


WHY NLB CANNOT DO MULTIPLE TG
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NLB has no rule engine
NLB just forwards TCP packets
it does not inspect traffic
so it cannot make routing decisions
like "send 20% here and 80% there"

ALB reads HTTP headers
ALB understands requests
ALB can make smart routing decisions


SUMMARY
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

                    ALB TG          NLB TG
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
has target group    ✅ yes          ✅ yes
multiple TGs        ✅ yes          ❌ no
weighted routing    ✅ yes          ❌ no
Blue/Green          ✅ yes          ❌ no
Canary              ✅ yes          ❌ no
registers EC2       ✅ yes          ✅ yes
health checks       ✅ yes          ✅ yes
protocol            HTTP/HTTPS      TCP/UDP/TLS


INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

"NLB does have target groups but its listener
 can only forward to ONE target group.
 ALB listener supports multiple target groups
 with weights which is what enables Blue/Green
 and Canary.
 NLB has no rule engine to make routing
 decisions — it just forwards TCP packets
 to a single target group." ✅
